Explanation: The New York Botanical Garden was established in 1891 and the first structures on its grounds opened at the end of that decade. The Garden's creation followed a fund-raising campaign led by the Torrey Botanical Society and Columbia University botanist Nathaniel Lord Britton and his wife Elizabeth Gertrude Britton. The Garden occupied part of the grounds of the Lorillard estate and a parcel that was formerly the easternmost portion of the campus of St. John's College. The stated purpose of the act was to establish and maintain a botanical garden and museum and arboretum, to advance botanical science and knowledge, and to prosecute original researches in kindred subjects. The legislation provided 250 acres within Bronx Park to the NYBG and enabled the board of directors to construct a library and conservatory if at least $250,000 was raised within five years. The first structures to open at the NYBG were the LuEsther T. Mertz Library and the Enid A. Haupt Conservatory, which were built between 1897 and 1900 and completed in 1902, respectively. Therefore, the first scientific journal published by an organization located in the Bronx was likely published by the New York Botanical Garden around this time.

The Cape of Good Hope, then a British colony, annexed the port of Walvis Bay and the offshore Penguin Islands in 1878. The first Europeans to disembark and explore the region were traders and settlers from Germany and Sweden in the late 19th century. Dorsland Trekkers crossed the area on their way from the Transvaal to Angola in the late 19th century. Some of them settled in Namibia instead of continuing their journey.

The Prussian Lithuanians also experienced the same fate as the Germans. They were expelled by the Soviet Union. Only 219 Prussian Lithuanians lived along the Curonian Spit in 1955. Many had German names such as Fritz or Hans, a cause for anti-German discrimination. The Soviet authorities considered the Prussian Lithuanians fascists. Because of this discrimination, many immigrated to West Germany in 1958, where the majority of Prussian Lithuanians now live. After the expulsion of the German population, ethnic Russians, Belarusians, and Ukrainians were settled in the northern part. In the Soviet part of the region, a policy of eliminating all remnants of German history was pursued. All German place names were replaced by new Russian names. The exclave was a military zone, which was closed to foreigners; Soviet citizens could only enter with special permission. In 1967, the remnants of Königsberg Castle were demolished on the orders of Leonid Brezhnev to make way for a new 'House of the Soviets'.

Hans Albert Einstein was educated at ETH Zurich, where he studied civil engineering, graduating in 1926. From 1926 to 1930, he worked at the steel design company Klönne, in Dortmund, Germany. From 1931 to 1938, he worked as a research engineer at the newly founded Laboratory of Hydraulics and Soil Mechanics (VAWE) at ETH Zurich. There, in 1936 Hans Albert obtained a doctorate in technical science. His doctoral thesis "Bed Load Transport as a Probability Problem" (Der Geschiebetrieb als Wahrscheinlichkeitsproblem) is considered the definitive work on sediment transport. Hans emigrated from Switzerland to Greenville, South Carolina, in 1938, and worked for the US Department of Agriculture, studying sediment transport from 1938 to 1943. He continued working for the USDA at the California Institute of Technology starting in 1943. In 1947 he took a position as associate professor of hydraulic engineering at the University of California, Berkeley. He advanced to full professor, and later professor emeritus. Einstein traveled the world to participate in hydraulic engineering conferences. He was at a symposium at Woods Hole in Massachusetts when he collapsed and died from heart failure on July 26, 1973.
